Dostoevsky believes that the kind of person you are depends on your environment and heredity, but it's very important that it also depends on what happens to you when you're very young.

608
00:56:18,400 --> 00:56:22,080
So Yvonne and Alyasha have the same meek mother, Sophia.

609
00:56:22,081 --> 00:56:23,841
They're terribly different.

610
00:56:23,840 --> 00:56:27,921
And heredity can't explain that, and DNA can't explain that.

611
00:56:27,920 --> 00:56:29,681
What does explain that?

612
00:56:30,001 --> 00:56:34,880
Well, I'm going to go quick over some things.

613
00:56:34,880 --> 00:56:37,200
I just want to give you the context.

614
00:56:37,200 --> 00:56:52,961
So the question is: why are Alyasha and Dimitri in the Christian dimension, even though they've got different mothers, while Yvonne is a philosopher and a Platonist, even though he's got the same mother as Alyasha?

615
00:56:52,961 --> 00:57:04,801
And that is that somehow there's got to be experiences in their childhood, Dostoevsky thinks, that influence their fundamental take on their the self.

616
00:57:04,800 --> 00:57:07,360
It's a kind of Freudian idea, if that's any help.

617
00:57:07,360 --> 00:57:09,760
And you probably read Freud in some course or other.

618
00:57:09,760 --> 00:57:12,720
How many have come across Freud already?

619
00:57:13,481 --> 00:57:14,841
Not only a few.

620
00:57:13,441 --> 00:57:17,320
Well, anyway, I'll just give you a very quick thing.

621
00:57:17,481 --> 00:57:24,760
Dostoevsky, Freud thinks that childhood traumas are very important in shaping people's personality.

622
00:57:24,760 --> 00:57:27,481
A trauma is a painful, bad event.

623
00:57:27,481 --> 00:57:30,120
And Dostoevsky has the reverse view.

624
00:57:30,121 --> 00:57:34,761
He thinks that what's really important are positive childhood memories.

625
00:57:34,760 --> 00:57:41,400
Freud thinks that you have to repress these childhood traumas, and they're very hard to uncover in later years.

626
00:57:41,400 --> 00:57:44,121
And that's what the therapist has to help you do.

627
00:57:44,121 --> 00:57:54,040
Dostoevsky thinks that since these memories that are important are positive memories, they're not things that people repress, but things that people remember frequently.

628
00:57:54,041 --> 00:57:58,200
As he puts it every once in a while, they remember them all their lives.

629
00:57:58,200 --> 00:58:04,601
Now, and here we go now to one of them in Alyasha.

630
00:58:05,240 --> 00:58:07,881
Here's why Alyasha is different.

631
00:58:07,880 --> 00:58:11,321
Here's why Alyasha is in a spiritual dimension.

632
00:58:11,320 --> 00:58:18,681
And so here's he's saying on 17, second sentence of the first full paragraph.

633
00:58:18,681 --> 00:58:28,920
I've mentioned already that although he lost his mother in his fourth year, he remembered her all his life, her face, her caresses, as though she stood right before him.

634
00:58:29,081 --> 00:58:30,280
Remembered her all his life.

635
00:58:30,280 --> 00:58:35,481
You see, not repressed the memory of her, Freud-like, but kept it in front of him, so to speak.

636
00:58:35,481 --> 00:58:46,600
And he says such memories persist from an early age, from even two years old, and stand out through a whole lifetime, like spots of light out of darkness, and so forth and so forth.

637
00:58:46,601 --> 00:58:48,921
Now comes his childhood memory.

638
00:58:48,920 --> 00:58:55,081
He remembered, and it's all just absolutely amazing and fascinating what he remembers.

639
00:58:55,081 --> 00:59:01,041
