690
01:03:07,681 --> 01:03:11,681
And he laughed and said it as best he could, got their Heiligegeist.

691
01:03:11,681 --> 01:03:17,280
And I went away, and two days later I happened to be passing and he shouted to me, Uncle, got their father, got their son.

692
01:03:17,280 --> 01:03:19,360
He'd only forgotten Got their Heiligegeist.

693
01:03:19,360 --> 01:03:22,801
And I reminded him of it and felt sorry for him again.

694
01:03:22,800 --> 01:03:23,840
What's going on there?

695
01:03:23,840 --> 01:03:27,601
First, I was just leaving it the way it is here, but it's in German.

696
01:03:27,601 --> 01:03:30,320
Does anybody know what was just being said?

697
01:03:30,641 --> 01:03:35,521
God the Father, God the Son, and God the Holy Ghost, or God the Holy Spirit.

698
01:03:35,521 --> 01:03:41,281
And that's what the German doctor says as he gives him the pound of nuts.

699
01:03:41,280 --> 01:03:44,161
What in the world is going on there?

700
01:03:44,161 --> 01:03:54,401
That pound of nuts is going to be the thing that Dimitri remembers all his life as an act of love and caring of which he had very little.

701
01:03:54,400 --> 01:04:04,240
But that was enough to get him sensitive to the loving, caring dimension, just like Alyasha was sensitive to it when being held up to the icon.

702
01:04:04,240 --> 01:04:08,000
Because it turns out to be a lasting childhood memory.

703
01:04:08,001 --> 01:04:09,361
It would just go on.

704
01:04:09,360 --> 01:04:11,601
Then he was taken away, and I didn't see him again.

705
01:04:11,601 --> 01:04:14,440
23 years passed, and I'm sitting, this is the doctor talking.

706
01:04:14,601 --> 01:04:27,160
One morning in my study, a bald-headed old man, where there walks into the room a blooming young man who I never would have recognized, except that he held up his finger and said, laughing, got their father, got their son, and got their Heiligegeist.

707
01:04:27,161 --> 01:04:32,920
I have just arrived and have come to thank you for that pound of nuts, for no one ever brought me a pound of nuts.

708
01:04:32,920 --> 01:04:35,081
You were the only one who ever did.

709
01:04:35,081 --> 01:04:35,800
Okay.

710
01:04:36,441 --> 01:04:38,601
Can you tell what's going on there?

711
01:04:38,601 --> 01:04:47,561
On what occasion do you say to child or to a baby, God the Father, God the Son, baptism.

712
01:04:47,561 --> 01:04:48,840
This is baptism.

713
01:04:48,840 --> 01:05:00,921
Dostoevsky has the peculiar thing that when he's doing anything of this sort, I'll tell you what sort it is as I go, he tells you.

714
01:05:00,920 --> 01:05:02,600
So he's telling you what?

715
01:05:02,601 --> 01:05:19,240
That the German doctor baptized him, said over him the words that helped, that expressed the fact that he was entering the dimension of possible love and possible despair, the Christian dimension.

716
01:05:19,240 --> 01:05:27,161
And that's now one wants to say, look back at what happened with Alyasha when his mother held him up to the icon.

717
01:05:27,161 --> 01:05:38,841
That was also the same kind of baptism, only Dostoevsky didn't hit you over the head with it using the words that are used when you baptize a baby.

718
01:05:38,840 --> 01:05:41,801
And what is baptism for Dostoevsky?

719
01:05:41,800 --> 01:05:48,840
Well, it's getting a saving childhood memory that puts you in the Christian religious dimension.

720
01:05:48,840 --> 01:05:55,160
Now, the question is: what is he doing when he does this strange mood with baptism?

721
01:05:55,160 --> 01:05:57,160
Well, now that's very important.

722
01:05:57,160 --> 01:06:10,320
What Dostoevsky's doing is taking what looks just like some kind of magical formula where you say these special words, and lo and behold, the child somehow becomes part of the Christian community.

723
01:06:10,800 --> 01:06:20,160
And the point is, Dostoevsky's telling you the psychological, existential meaning of baptism, according to him.

724
01:06:20,321 --> 01:06:27,040
I mean, baptism is just a kind of magic, and he wants to get all the magic out of Christianity.

725
01:06:27,040 --> 01:06:39,601
And he wants to replace the magic with an existential account of what it does to the person's psychology to have these Christian rituals.

726
01:06:39,601 --> 01:06:43,840
And now, and we'll see what I want to say next.

727
01:06:45,441 --> 01:07:06,000
The whole book on one level is dedicated to the project of saving Christianity by converting all the magical mystery things that happen in Christianity into existential things.

728
01:07:06,000 --> 01:07:08,000
He's demagicalizing it.

729
01:07:08,241 --> 01:07:12,641
The way theologians talk, he's demythologizing Christianity.

730
01:07:12,641 --> 01:07:14,000
I think that's a bad move.

731
01:07:14,000 --> 01:07:20,720
The student pointed out: myths are good things, and we don't want to demythologize.

732
01:07:20,720 --> 01:07:22,641
But magic isn't a good thing.

733
01:07:22,641 --> 01:07:23,920
And why isn't it?

734
01:07:23,920 --> 01:07:37,760
Because you don't want to get yourself in the position of thinking of Christianity as some kind of causal thing, in which those magic words said over the baby transform the baby in some way.

735
01:07:37,760 --> 01:07:41,601
That's, if you do that, you're in serious trouble.

736
01:07:41,601 --> 01:07:51,641
Because if you start thinking of Christianity as sort of magical ways of causing things, then you run up against the laws of physics and chemistry and neuroscience.

737
01:07:51,641 --> 01:08:01,720
Believe it or not, Dostoevsky has already just gotten news of neuroscience, and that seems to compete with these Christian magical practices.

738
01:08:01,720 --> 01:08:07,000
But if there are these existential practices, then there's no conflict.

739
01:08:07,000 --> 01:08:17,000
And Dostoevsky is very dedicated to this, between the laws of physics and chemistry, and we can now add genetics and evolution, and the truth of Christianity.

740
01:08:17,000 --> 01:08:23,960
But that requires converting every one of the Christian symbols into an existential experience.

741
01:08:23,960 --> 01:08:27,240
And you just saw baptism converted.

742
01:08:27,241 --> 01:08:32,440
And Dostoevsky has this game, which I find just wonderful, and you have to learn to play it.

743
01:08:32,441 --> 01:08:42,440
He never misses a chance to tell you once and once and clearly which Christian thing he has just existentialized.

744
01:08:42,441 --> 01:08:45,960
That's why the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit gets in there.

745
01:08:46,281 --> 01:08:49,960
When you give somebody a bag of nuts, it's not the normal thing to say.

746
01:08:49,960 --> 01:08:58,760
You'll see, I'll just read it now in a minute, Beatrice, that he wants to existentialize.

